 take its name from a hill named with Old English <i>mamme</i> ‘teat’) + Old English <i>feld</i> ‘open country’.","Irish (Waterford): when not an importation of 1, this is an altered form of the Norman name <b>de Manville</b> (see   Mandeville   3).","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) <b>Mansfeld</b>, a habitational name from a place so called in Saxony."]},{"name":"Manderville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Manwell","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Manville","meanings":["English (Sussex and Lancashire): variant of   Mandeville  .","Altered form of   Mainville   1, a surname of Swiss French origin (see   Miville  ).","French: variant of <b>Menville</b>, a habitational name from Menville in Haute-Garonne, and also of   Mainville   2."]},{"name":"Mundell","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  .","Americanized form of German <b>Mündel</b> (or some other similar, like-sounding surname): nickname for someone with a prominent mouth, from Middle High German <i>munt</i>, <i>mündelīn</i> ‘(little) mouth’."]},{"name":"Monville","meanings":["Altered form of French   Mandeville  .","Walloon: habitational name from Monville in Namur province in Wallonia (Belgium), of the same etymology as in 3 below.","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Montville in Seine-Maritime or Monville in Calvados, both named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘mountain, hill’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’."]},{"name":"Mandal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Chandi, Sanjay, Sankar, Somnath, Aditi, Aditya, Ajit, Amala, Amitabha, Anil, Anirudh, Aparna.","Indian (northern states): from Sanskrit <i>maṇḍala</i>, a word that has several meanings, including ‘sphere’ and ‘halo’.","English (Cumbria; of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Montville","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Vernice.","Altered form of French   Mandeville  .","French: variant of   Monville  . This surname is very rare in France, found mainly in Creuse."]},{"name":"Manfull","meanings":["English (Midlands): probably a variant of   Mandeville  . Compare   Manville  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705179,"age":7,"year":"1013","julianDay":2091051,"title":"Sweyn Forkbeard","description":"The Danes raided and captured England. Sweyn, King of Danes, was declared King of England on Christmas Day.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweyn_Forkbeard","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Sweyn Forkbeard","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705180,"age":10,"year":"1016","julianDay":2092146,"title":"Canut the Great","description":"As Aethelred, King of England died, his son, Edmund Ironside devised a truce with Danish King Canute. The truce divided the kingdom between the two but Edmund died shortly after and became King of England. Several years later, he also became king of Denmark.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cnut_the_Great","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Cnut the Great","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705181,"age":29,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William Maneville was born in 1006, in Rycote, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with William de Mandeville. She died in London, Middlesex, England."},"et":{"1006–":"1006–Surnud","1006–Male":"1006–Surnud","1036–1144":"1036–1144","1006–Female":"1006–Surnud","1006":"1006","1016":"1016","Abt 1036":"umbes 1036","1036":"1036","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1144":"1144","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1006–":"1006–Kuollut","1006–Male":"1006–Kuollut","1036–1144":"1036–1144","1006–Female":"1006–Kuollut","1006":"1006","1016":"1016","Abt 1036":"noin 1036","1036":"1036","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1144":"1144","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1006–":"1006–Décédée","1006–Male":"1006–Décédé","1036–1144":"1036–1144","1006–Female":"1006–Décédée","1006":"1006","1016":"1016","Abt 1036":"environ 1036","1036":"1036","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1144":"1144","London, Middlesex, England":"Londres, Middlesex, Angleterre","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Normandy, France":"Normandie, France","lifeSummary":"Mrs. William Maneville est née en 1006, à Rycote, Oxfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec William de Mandeville. Elle est décédée à Londres, Middlesex, Angleterre."},"de":{"1006–":"1006–Verstorben","1006–Male":"1006–Verstorben","1036–1144":"1036–1144","1006–Female":"1006–Verstorben","1006":"1006","1016":"1016","Abt 1036":"um 1036","1036":"1036","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1